  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Water Risk and its Management in Bolivia&apos;s Altiplano Development Strategy</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Water resources in Bolivia, especially in the highlands, are under huge pressure as a result of inappropriate development, population growth and climate variability.   The proper management of water resources, underpinned by scientific research, is therefore essential if the country is to prosper in the future.

This project &#x201C;Water Risk and its Management in Bolivia&apos;s Altiplano Development Strategy&#x201D; is the first component of the UCL &#x2013; CAFOD &#x2013; CENDA &#x2013; CIPCA research partnership looking at Water Management in Bolivia&#x2019;s Development Strategy. The aim of the project is to assess the risks and management scenarios relating to water resources on the Bolivian Altiplano. A component of the project will also look at the rules governing the use of scarce common-pool water and how these are being transformed and with what effects. The overall purpose of the project is to inform development models in the context of the effective management of the quantity and quality of water.

The main project team will consist of a Post-Doctoral Research Associate (PDRA) based in the UCL Institute for Risk and Disaster Reduction (IRDR) and the Aon Benfield UCL Hazard Centre (ABUHC) and an environmental researcher based with CAFOD partner CENDA in Bolivia.</narrative>
  </description>
